‘The Federation of Cherry Oak and Victoria Schools
Role of the Safeguarding Governor

Objective:

‘As the governor responsible for safeguarding children, you will play an essential role in ensuring
children in these schools are kept safe from harm. The safeguarding governor plays an important
role in ensuring oversight and scrutiny of safeguarding policy, procedure and practice on behalf of
the full governing body. It is recognized that Governors are volunteers and generously give of their
time, interest and expertise to the ultimate benefit of children in our schools but it should not be
underestimated that your role is that of a ‘senior manager’ of a school with accountability befiting
‘such a significant responsibilty

Your role as Nominated Governor for Safeguarding is to:

+ Actas a‘crlical friend’ to the school, in order to ensure that the appropriate systems and.
procedures are in place to cover all aspects of the safeguarding agenda and all statutory
governing body responsibilities are met.

‘+ Monitor appropriate policies, including the safeguarding and whistle blowing policies.

+ Ensure there is a suitably qualified, rained and supported Designated Senior Person who
has responsibilty for responding to and overseeing safeguarding issues.

+ Ensure there is a suitably qualified, rained and supported Deputy Designated Person who
has responsibilty for responding to and overseeing safeguarding issues as agreed
reasonable to be delegated by the DSP.

+ Ensure that the DSP adequately supervises and supports the work, development and
wellbeing of the DDP and any other individual to whom they may delegate additional
‘safeguarding responsibilities in order that there exist clear lines of accountability.

+ Ensure there is a robust system for recording, storing and reviewing child welfare concerns.

+ Liaise with the head about general child protection and broader safeguarding issues within
the school and as such be able to provide reports to the governing body in respect of
themes and issues within the schooVocality to enable adequate oversight, understanding
and development of solutions.

+ Ensure that school staff training is up to date. Attend Basic Awareness Safeguarding
training every 3 years and other training as appropriate to the role and relevant to issues
within the school/locality

+ Ensure other governors attend appropriate safeguarding training.

Gentle soothing or motivational music
Journaling

Arts and crafts

Deep breathing

Meditation

Progressive muscle relaxation

Reminders about the reasons to get better
Origami

Card games

Conversation

Some helpful suggestions that YP have used here at Highfield include:

* Making cheerleading cards
* Colouring

* Reading

* Bananagrams

CC: 79/2016 2016 S. NO.8 between Sierra Blocks Concrete Products Company

Nonetheless, the failure of Fornah-Sesay, Cummings, Showers and Co. to fully

+ Good morning. | wish to thank Chairman Barrett
and the committee for allowing me to speak
today. My name is Pat Clements. |ama
pediatrician who takes care of newborn babies in
the hospital. | speak in support of this bill on behalf
of the Indiana Chapter of the American Academy of
Pediatrics (others)

+ This bill creates a pathway through which new
conditions can be approved for inclusion on the
newborn screen. The newborn screen is a blood
test that babies get after birth that tests for dozens
of rare, but treatable, serious medical
conditions. As doctors, it is important to know
about these conditions quickly. As medical
advances occur, there will be opportunities to add
new conditions to the newborn screen.

+ This bill would create an advisory council that would
bring together a multidisciplinary team from across
our state, including experts in genetics, metabolism,
hematology, and neonatology. It would also bring
together family advocates and experts in public
health, laboratory medicine, and medical ethics.

+ This new process will allow a clear and defined
pathway that families, patient advocate groups, and
healthcare providers can use to nominate a
condition to be added to the newborn screen.

European Foundry Industry Sentiment, August 2020:
European foundries continue to face no positive outlook
after the Covid-19 outbreak.

‘Attera sharp drop and its lowest level in May, the Business Climate Incicator forthe euro area
recovered for the third time in a row in August. However, the signs of recovery have so far not
‘been reflactedin the mood among foundries. The European Foundry Industry Sentiment (FISI),

src_text:
Conclusion

‘The above eases of the Commonwealth Caribbean clealy reveal different approaches to
interpreting freedom of religion as a fundamental human right and as a constitutional right,
‘The ruling in the fist ease, R v Hines and King" shows clear accommodation, to allow for
the protection of two rights, namely, due process and freedom of conscience. Inthe second
case, Hinds v AG of Barbados,” there was an outright denial of te right o the extent that
there was no opportunity to even apply the compelling state interest est

In the third example involving Shemaiah Grant,” two rights the right to freedom of
Conscience and the right of every child to receive an education, were undermined. The final
<ecision inthe case involving Sumayyah Mohammed allowed for an exemption to the
application of legislation saved by the very constitution which allowed for the observance of
aright protected by the supreme law of the land, the Constitution.

‘This later decision is heralded as the return of prudence to interpretation. Iis the kind of
decision that makes the distinction between having the egal right to do something and doing
the right thing.

‘Courts have the power to adopt a generous ifeven strained meaning if this is required to
make legislation compatible with human or constitutional rights. They must avoid the
austerity of tabulated legalism and see the Constitutions as living and always speaking,
never silent

In concluding, permit me to recast a famous extra-judicial quote of Justice Kirby of the High
‘Court of Australia in his Hamlyn Lectures: “As another sage put it: you construe human
rights not as your first but your last rights, that is what they will become, obsequies.”

01 Health and safety procedures

01.7 Outdoors

All gates and fences are childproof, safe, and secure,

+ Areas are checked daily to make sure animal droppings, litter, glass etc, is removed, Staff wear

rubber gloves to do this,
+ Bushes or overhanging trees are checked to ensure they do not bear poisonous berries

+ Stinging nettles and brambles are removed

+ Safety mots ore provided under climbing equipment, even when on grass

+ Wooden equipment is maintained safely, put away daily and not used if broken,

+ Wooden equipment is sanded and varnished as required

+ Broken climbing equipment or outdoor toys are removed and reported to the setting manager.
+ Ghildren are always supervised within ratios outside

+ Children are suitably aired for the weather conditions and type of outdoor activities

+ Sun cream (if parents have given permission) is applied and hats are worn during the summer

months. Outdoor play is avoided in extreme heat between noon and 3pm.

Children who have no adequate means of sun protection, such as a hat, long sleeves and trousers
fr sun cream, will not be able to play outdoors in un-shaded areas, Tf extremely hot outdoor play

is restricted

+ Children are supervised on climbing equipment, especially younger children

+ Water play is not left out but is cleared, cleaned and stored after each use

+ Receptacles are left upturned to prevent collection of rainwater, this is important in areas where
‘there are vermin to prevent urine/faeces contaminating the water.

‘Sightings of vermin are recorded and reported to the manager who reports to the community
centre management team who contact the pest control agent for the building

+ Tf paddling pools are used, a risk assessment is conducted, and consideration given to the needs
of disabled children or those less ambulant.

Desertification: Fertile land turning into desert. As soil becomes more degraded,
nutrients decrease and vegetation cannot be supported.

Dust storms: Soil becomes less stable and more vulnerable to wind erosion (Gobi
Desert)

Topsoil erosion: Nutrient rich, humus layer reduces and causes more erosion.
Reduced crop yields: Failing crop yields can lead to famine, starvation and has
‘economic impacts on local farmers.

Conflict: With the reduction of agricultural output and land, conflict may arise over
resources.

Increased use of chemicals: Fertilizers may increase to compensate for the lack of
natural nutrients, worsening the problem.

Solutions to soil degradation:

Crop rotation and fallow periods: The soil can regain ferility and nultients.
Terracing and contour ploughing: Ploughing with shape and terracing reduces
water erosion.

Shelter belts (wind breaks): Forests or hedges that protect farmland and reduce
wind and water erosion

Reforestation and afforestation: Trees make land more stable and fertile.
Population control: Decreases agricultural demand.

Urban planning: Reduces the need to detorest.

Grazing quotas: Limits in number of animals that graze.

GM Crops: Crops withstand poor conditions and increase yields.

荒漠化：肥沃的土地变成沙漠。随着土壤变得越来越降解，
营养减少，植被无法支持。

沙尘暴：土壤变得不那么稳定，更容易受到风侵蚀（戈壁
沙漠）

表土侵蚀：富含营养的腐殖质层减少并导致更多侵蚀。
作物产量降低：农作物产量失败会导致饥荒，饥饿，并具有
‘经济对当地农民的影响。

冲突：随着农业产出和土地的减少，可能会发生冲突
资源。

增加化学物质的使用：肥料可能会增加以弥补缺乏
天然营养素，使问题恶化。

土壤降解的解决方案：

作物旋转和休耕时期：土壤可以恢复易态性和杂种。
梯田和轮廓耕作：耕作形状和梯田降低
水侵蚀。

避难带（风力休息）：保护农田并减少的森林或树篱
风向侵蚀

造林和造林：树木使土地更稳定和肥沃。
人口控制：减少农业需求。

城市规划：减少了破坏性的需求。

放牧配额：放牧动物数量的限制。

转基因作物：农作物承受不良状况和增加产量。

said he made himself a slave to everyone to win them to Christ and
to share in the Gospel’s blessings. (1 Cor 9:19-23)

+ In II Corinthians God says our letters of recommendation are not
written with ink, but are written with the Spirit of the Living God on
the human heart, and that we as Christians are the letters of
recommendation read to other Christians and to all men. We don’t
need man’s evaluation of our lives — we need God’s. (II Cor 3:1-6)

+ Inthe book of Ephesians God calls us to live a life worthy of the
calling we have received and to be completely humble and gentle.
(Eph 4:1-6)

+ In Philippians God tells us to be content whatever the circumstances
and that we can do all things through Christ who strengthens us. We
need to be happy with what we have not dissatisfied. (Phil 4:10-13)

+ God encourages us to do our good deeds with humility and not to
harbor bitter envy and selfish ambition in our hearts which is of the
devil and breeds disorder and every evil practice. (James 3:13-16)

+ James tells us that if we are in humble circumstances we ought to
take pride in our high position; but that if we are not and are rich,
we should take pride in his low position. (James 1:9-11)

+ Peter and James encourage us to clothe ourselves in humility
toward one another because God opposes the proud and gives grace
to the humble; and to humble ourselves because God will lift us up
in due time. (1 Peter 5:1-9; 1 Peter 3:8; James 4:10)

“Do not be ashamed to serve others for the love of Jesus Christ and to
seem poor in this world. Do not be self-sufficient but place your trust
in God. Do what lies in your power and God will aid your good will.

Put no trust in your own learning nor in the cunning of any man, but

Engine to flatten. She did not want to let them down, so she flashed by at
full speed and flattened the copper circles into ovals. The young writers
collected their new treasure, sprinted down the tracks and hopped back on.

‘The curving country roads passed by as they gazed out the windows.

‘The Innovative Engine came upon the Appalachian Mountains, and pulled

up on her brakes with a screeeeeeech. Steve, a young writer, wrote in his

journal: “The mountains stretch on like giant gopher mounds as far as the

eye can see.”
‘The Innovative Engine remembered the story of alittle engine who believed
in himself to make it over a mountain, but she stated, “I think I can, I think I
can, [think I can come up with a better way!” She asked the young writers
to blast a tunnel through the mountain using dynamite. Ssssssss, Pop, Pow,
Boooooom!

Breathing her exhaust in the tunnel made everyone cough and wheeze. The
young writers tucked their noses under their t-shirts. “I should run on
renewable energy,” she thought aloud. The young writers researched solar
energy and ordered solar panels online. They installed them the next day.

Churn, Burn, Turn! Flip, Flap, Snap!

src_text:
How can I help my child?

Help him/her to learn to put on his coat independently now that the
weather is turning colder.

Help your child to be independent at using the toilet and washing his/her
hands,

Talk to your child about what he/she has done at nursery - but try not to
quiz them!

Look at the Rhyme of the Week and try to say/sing this at home as well
Help your child to count to 10, Count as you go up and down the stairs at
bedtime, Also help him/her to count a few items (using a counting finger).
This could be using your nursery book after bedtime story, cars in the
road, peas on your plate- anything!

Encourage your child to cut out pictures and hold the scissors up the
right way. We have children’s scissors which you can buy in nursery,
Encourage your child to choose a different book each day from our book
corner, Have fun telling the stories in our new storybags.

Talk with your child about colour names, animal names etc. We have lots
‘of books which provide opportunities for this on our bookcase.

Encourage your child to do simple jigsaws - 6.10.12 pieces as these help
children to look carefully and develop hand eye co-ordination.

Invite another child from nursery to come and play so that they can
practise sharing and turn taking,

Visit the library - they have some great books.

Have fun together!

我该如何帮助我的孩子？

现在，帮助他/她学会独立穿外套
天气变冷。

帮助您的孩子独立使用厕所并洗涤他/她
手，

与您的孩子谈谈他/她在托儿所所做的事情 - 但请不要

看看本周的押韵，然后尝试在家中说/唱歌

这可能是在睡前的故事后使用您的托儿书，汽车在
道路，豌豆在你的盘子上 - 任何东西！

鼓励您的孩子剪掉图片，并将剪刀固定
正道。我们有可以在托儿所购买的儿童剪刀，
鼓励您的孩子每天从我们的书中选择另一本书

与您的孩子谈论颜色名称，动物名称等

孩子们仔细地看并发展手眼协调。

邀请另一个来自托儿所的孩子来玩，以便他们可以
练习共享和转弯，

访问图书馆 - 他们有一些很棒的书。

一起玩！

NOTES from Greenwich Council Meeting with EGRA and other local interest groups.
‘Thursday 13 November 2014, at the Greenwich Social Club, Tunnel Avenue.

PLEASE NOTE:
‘These are notes made during the meeting by EGRA members, and are not officially agreed
minutes.

Present from Greenwich Council
Clr Matthew Pennycook (Labour Parliamentary Candidate)
Clr Danny Thorpe, Cabinet Member for Regeneration

Clr Chris Lloyd (Peninsula Ward)

Cllr Denise Scott McDonald (Peninsula Ward)

Mike Hows, AD Planning

Tim Jackson, AD Transport

Pippa Hack, Director Regeneration & Transport

Representatives from:
EGRA; Greenwich Society; ‘No ikea’ Campaign; Lorraine Turton from East Greenwich
Business Association; Safer Neighbourhood Partnership; Westcombe Society, Greenwich
Conservation Society

(Mike Hows presented for first 30 minutes of the meeting:
Gave an update and overview of four ‘master plans’ for regeneration within the borough,
which were published in 2012.Masterplans are for: Eitham Town Centre, Woolwich Town
Centre, Charlton Riverside (with a new park), Peninsula. The West Greenwich Creekside
‘development was coming to the end of its cycle. Charlton Riverside plans would see 5,000,
new homes, an educational campus and the integration of retail

‘A masterplan for peninsular West was drafted in 2012 which still stands, but this isan
aspirational document only with educational and sports facilities and plans for an Arena.

He presented some historical perspective and some future considerations. He referred to
several planning and development documents, including ‘Royal Greenwich Local Plan’; ‘Core
Strategy with Detailed Policies’ document.

ACTION FOR EGRA: obtain copy of this document (should be on the RBG website}

He set out the Council's responsibility for looking at areas for investment and areas for
protection across the borough. Woolwich will Become a ‘metropolitan centre’ (Ultimately
more development than the Peninsula), and the impact that Cross Ral would have on the
‘entire Borough was highlighted. The point was made strongly by Mathew Pennycook that
‘we would benefit from Cross ail as it would take away some of the traffic coming from the
‘east, so that the tube/bus/train would be emptier by the time it reached East Greenwich,

Peninsula:
Master plan agreed in 2004 was for 10,000 homes

Knight Dragon; development on the east side includes 50% affordable housing. West side of
Peninsula is being re-thought. Peninsula West SDP 2012 - issues: gas holder &Bretang

src_text:
1.3 Guiding Principles for the Youth Policy

The Narok County Youth Policy seeks to appreciate the stipulation of the
Constitution of Kenya 2010 and especially the National Values and Principle of
Governance under Article 10. The Narok County Youth Policy therefore becomes
‘a vehicle for prioritizing critical actions aimed at creating an enabling
environment for the youth to fully achieve their aspirations as County
Government of Narok residents. The Policy addresses key strategies needed to
engage the youth in ensuring their active participation and holistic engagement
in actualizing National Values and Principles of Governance. The key principles
guiding the implementation of the Narok County Youth Policy are;

Empowerment:

Youth in Narok County shall be empowered to take control of their own lives and
destiny and take full responsibilities of their action while influencing their own
future to trigger positive change

‘Transparency:

Institutions and organizations involved in Youth development in Narok County
should operate in a transparent and accountable manner and trigger positive

change
Participation:

‘The views of the youth and their participation in county development must be
sought. Narok County and other stakeholders must consciously and consistently
involve young people in planning and decision-making processes that affect them

and wider society.

Enabling women's workforce participation also contributes to women’s greater
‘economic security and greater productivity across the economy. It has been noted
that increasing women’s participation in the workforce by 6 per cent could contribute
to increasing Australia's gross domestic product by $25 billion.'«

‘A Toolkit for workplaces to support unpaid carers

‘This Toolkit is designed to assist managers and staff in the workplace to find
constructive and sustainable solutions that support unpaid carers to remain engaged
and productive at work.

For the purposes of this Toolkit, ‘staff’ can include anyone who works for the
‘organisation, irrespective of their type of employment, their employment contract or
arrangement, hours worked, or status as permanent, casual or temporary.

‘This Toolkit focuses on strategies workplaces can use to support unpaid carers in
being able to meet their caring responsibilities while continuing to work.

‘The Toolkit provides practical suggestions and examples of different kinds of
workplace mechanisms to support carers in organisations and workplaces of all sizes
land types. These examples have been drawn from current practice both within
‘Australia and overseas. Practices were sourced from 24 countries. Some of the
‘suggested workplace mechanisms will suit small organisations, while others will be
more suitable for large organisations.

‘The Australian Human Rights Commission's Valuing Unpaid Caring Work in Australia
Research Project investigated the nature of unpaid caring work in Australia. The
Project focused on the impact unpaid caring work has on the carer's participation in
ppald work in addition to their retirement savings over their lifetime. Read more about

the Project and the report at www.humanrights.gov.au/about/publications!. This
Toolkit is a companion resource to the Project's research report.

src_text:
Schizotypal personality disorder

A person with a schizotypal personality disorder
is likely to have poor social skills and delusional
thoughts, and behave in unusual ways.

Other features include:

attaching undue and misguided significance to everyday events - such
as thinking newspaper headlines are secret messages to them

+ believing in special powers - such as telepathy or the ability to influence
other people's emotions and actions

+ having unusual ways of speaking - such as long, rambling vague
sentences or going off on a tangent

+ experiencing excessive anxiety in social situations - even if they have
known a particular person or group of people a long time

‘Showcasing the DNR: Treasure trove of deer data on the way with
mandatory online harvest reporting

By CASEY WARNER
Michigan Department of Natural Resources

Michigan’s annual deer hunting seasons ~ to many, as much a fall tradition as football,
‘apple cider and pumpkin patches ~ are once again underway.

‘The Liberty Hunt, for youth hunters and those with disabilities, the early antlerless
firearm season and the Independence Hunt, for hunters with disabilities, have already
‘come and gone. We're well into the archery season and, as we head into firearm
‘season, starting Nov. 15, hundreds of thousands of Michigan hunters will be headed
afield to pursue white-tailed deer.

‘Those who succeed in that pursuit will need to add one more step to their annual deer
hunting ritual ~ reporting their harvest online to the Michigan Department of Natural
Resources.

Starting with the fall 2022 deer seasons, all hunters who successfully take a deer are
required to report it through the DNR's online harvest reporting system.

This new reporting system is something many hunters have been requesting for several
years. During ths first fall with mandatory online reporting, conservation officers will
{focus on educating hunters on the new process, rather than issuing tickets, then begin
enforcement next year.

Since the 1950s, the DNR has gathered deer harvest information by mailing surveys to
‘a sample of hunters.

“The new system represents a major change for all Michigan hunters,” DNR deer, elk
‘and moose management specialist Chad Stewart said. “The system will provide us a
near real-time estimate of deer harvest as it occurs, something Michigan has never
‘experienced betore.”

‘One of the most important reasons for the move to online harvest reporting, according
to Stewart, is more data.

“For anyone out there who is a deer data nerd like myself, a treasure chest of
information is right around the corner

Better deer data

‘The DNR has traditionally gathered most deer harvest information through check
stations and mail surveys.
